The paper presents a novel distributed coverage control framework for a network of mobile agents, which involves unsupervised learning and clustering algorithms. This suggests that the paper could belong to the sub-category of Multi-Agent Systems (cs.MA), which deals with the coordination and control of multiple agents in a distributed setting. Additionally, the paper focuses on the coverage control problem, which involves the deployment of agents to cover a set of points of interest (PoI), which could fall under the sub-category of Robotics (cs.RO) or Systems and Control (cs.SY). The proposed algorithm also involves proximity constraints, which could be related to the sub-category of Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI), which deals with the development of intelligent agents and decision-making processes. Finally, the paper mentions the potential applications of the proposed framework in disaster relief, which could be related to the sub-category of Machine Learning (cs.LG), which deals with the development of algorithms that can learn from data and make predictions.
